<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Tannins to Salmon's Fat Content</strong> - Wild salmon's leaner flesh pairs beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Côte de Beaune Pinot Noir, while fatty farmed Atlantic salmon can handle the structured tannins of Loire Valley Cabernet Franc. The omega-3 oils in fattier salmon actually soften wine tannins, creating a more harmonious pairing than you'd expect with red wine and fish.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Consider Salmon Preparation Method First</strong> - Grilled or cedar-plank salmon develops smoky, caramelized flavors that complement oaked Chardonnay or even light Syrah from cooler climates like Northern Rhône. Raw preparations like sashimi or tartare require high-acidity wines like Sancerre or Muscadet to cut through the rich, buttery texture without overwhelming delicate flavors.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Temperature Precision Enhances the Pairing</strong> - Serve white wines at 50-54°F for salmon pairings—slightly warmer than typical white wine service. This temperature allows the wine's texture to better complement salmon's meaty consistency while preserving the acidity needed to balance the fish's natural oils. Light reds should be served at 60-62°F, cooler than room temperature.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Choose Glassware Based on Wine Body and Salmon Fat</strong> - Use a Burgundy glass for Pinot Noir with salmon to concentrate the wine's delicate aromatics and complement the fish's subtle flavors. For crisp whites like Albariño or Vermentino, use a smaller white wine glass to maintain the wine's bright acidity that cuts through salmon's richness.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Account for Salmon Species in Wine Selection</strong> - King salmon's buttery richness pairs exceptionally with aged white Burgundy or Viognier, while Sockeye's more intense flavor can stand up to rosé Champagne or Provence rosé. Coho salmon's moderate oil content makes it perfect for Grüner Veltliner or unoaked Chardonnay from cool climates.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Most Salmon Wine Pairings</strong> - Salmon's delicate flavors are best complemented by wines served directly from the bottle to preserve their fresh, primary fruit characteristics. The exception is mature Burgundy (8+ years), which benefits from 30 minutes of breathing to soften and integrate with salmon's subtle complexities.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Timing Matters for Optimal Flavor Integration</strong> - Open aromatic whites like Riesling or Gewürztraminer 15 minutes before serving with salmon to allow their bouquet to develop, enhancing the overall sensory experience. However, serve Champagne or Crémant immediately upon opening to maintain the effervescence that provides textural contrast to salmon's richness.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Seasonal Salmon Changes Require Different Wine Styles</strong> - Spring salmon's leaner profile from winter feeding pairs best with mineral-driven wines like Muscadet or Verdicchio, while late-season salmon with higher fat content can handle richer styles like white Rhône blends or even light Beaujolais served slightly chilled.</li>
</ol>



