    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with farmed vs. wild salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Wild salmon's leaner, more intense flavor pairs beautifully with structured wines like Oregon Pinot Noir or white Burgundy, while farmed salmon's higher fat content and milder taste works better with richer wines like oaked Chardonnay or Rhône Valley whites. The oil content in farmed salmon can handle more robust wines that would overpower wild salmon's delicate flavor. Consider the preparation method too – grilled wild salmon needs different wine support than cedar-plank farmed salmon.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine at different temperatures when pairing with hot vs. cold salmon dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, temperature contrast enhances the pairing experience significantly. Serve white wines slightly warmer (50-55°F) with hot salmon preparations like grilled or roasted fish to prevent the wine from tasting thin against the warm dish. For cold salmon dishes like sashimi or smoked salmon, serve whites at standard cellar temperature (45-50°F) and light reds slightly chilled (55-60°F) to complement the cool, delicate flavors without overwhelming them.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine mistakes do people make most often with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic, which clash with salmon's delicate oils and can create a metallic aftertaste. Avoid big Cabernets, oaky reds, or overly buttery Chardonnays with simply prepared salmon. Another common error is ignoring the sauce or preparation method – a wine perfect for plain grilled salmon might completely miss the mark with teriyaki or dill-crusted preparations.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is salmon wine pairing good for beginners who don't know much about wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely – salmon is one of the most forgiving proteins for wine pairing because it works well with both white and light red wines. Start with food-friendly options like Pinot Grigio, unoaked Chardonnay, or Pinot Noir, which are hard to get wrong with salmon. The fish's natural oils and mild flavor provide a great canvas for learning how different wine styles interact with food without overwhelming your palate.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget alternative to expensive Burgundy for salmon pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oregon Pinot Noir offers similar elegance and salmon-friendly characteristics as red Burgundy at half the price, with producers like Elk Cove and Argyle delivering excellent value. For white wine alternatives to white Burgundy, try Chablis from smaller producers or high-quality Albariño from Rías Baixas, which provides the same crisp minerality and citrus notes that complement salmon beautifully. These alternatives maintain the sophistication without the premium price tag.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do different salmon cooking methods change the wine pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops smoky, caramelized flavors that pair wonderfully with medium-bodied wines like Côtes du Rhône or aged Rioja, while poached salmon's delicate preparation calls for lighter wines like Sancerre or German Riesling. Smoked salmon's intense, salty character demands wines with bright acidity like Champagne or Muscadet to cut through the richness. Pan-seared salmon with its crispy skin can handle slightly more robust wines than other preparations.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair the same wine with salmon sushi and cooked salmon dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While possible, it's not ideal since the preparations create completely different flavor profiles and textural experiences. Raw salmon sushi pairs best with crisp, clean wines like Albariño or sake, which won't compete with the fish's pure, delicate flavor and the subtle soy and wasabi accompaniments. Cooked salmon can handle wines with more body and complexity, making a single wine choice less than optimal for both preparations.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines work best with salmon when dining outdoors or at picnics?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Choose wines that taste good slightly warmer and don't require precise serving temperatures – Provence rosé, Vinho Verde, and Loire Valley Sauvignon Blanc are perfect outdoor options that complement grilled or cold salmon preparations. Avoid delicate wines like aged Burgundy that suffer in heat, and opt for screw-cap bottles for convenience. These wines maintain their refreshing qualities even when they warm up slightly in outdoor settings.</p>
